WEBVTT

1
00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:18.800
All right. Committee, we have our final submitter for the afternoon.

2
00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:22.340
We have Nicholas Bernhardt from Informed365.

3
00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:28.380
Hopefully, Nicholas, you've accepted the invitation to become a panelist.

4
00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:31.980
There you go. Look at that. Efficient. Welcome. Hello. We have 10 minutes.

5
00:00:32.021 --> 00:00:32.381
Hello, how are you?

6
00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:35.520
Very well. We have 10 minutes with you this afternoon.

7
00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:38.920
That 10 minutes includes time for questions from the committee.

8
00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:41.800
You can take your submission as read, but it's always good to go through and

9
00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:44.360
highlight the things that you want us to be well across.

10
00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:45.720
Perfect.

11
00:00:48.440 --> 00:00:49.880
Do you want me to start now?

12
00:00:50.020 --> 00:00:51.220
Yes, please. Go for it. Sorry.

13
00:00:51.880 --> 00:00:55.670
Perfect. No, kia ora. I'm Nicholas Bernhardt from Informed365,

14
00:00:56.490 --> 00:00:59.640
and I appreciate the opportunity to speak to the committee today.

15
00:01:00.140 --> 00:01:04.130
For context, we work with around 500 organizations

16
00:01:04.181 --> 00:01:07.870
across all sectors in both Australia and New Zealand,

17
00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:11.970
including more than 150 that work through industry

18
00:01:12.060 --> 00:01:15.920
consortia on modern slavery compliance and supplier risk management.

19
00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:20.020
So we see directly what works and what doesn't in practice,

20
00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:24.040
and in this sort of session, I'd love to make three very clear

21
00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:27.680
points. The first one is proportionality.

22
00:01:28.220 --> 00:01:32.020
So I've read the submissions to this bill, and there's sort of a real

23
00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:33.380
concern that emerges.

24
00:01:34.280 --> 00:01:38.260
The idea that every business should do the same level of due diligence,

25
00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:42.240
regardless of size or actual risk, that's not really how it

26
00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:46.030
works in practice. These sort of small and medium-sized businesses

27
00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:48.460
we work with tell us they're overwhelmed.

28
00:01:49.070 --> 00:01:52.980
They're drowning in complex surveys and compliance demands from their

29
00:01:53.020 --> 00:01:56.740
larger customers, even when their risk sometimes

30
00:01:56.860 --> 00:01:57.880
is very low.

31
00:01:58.820 --> 00:02:01.580
And here's the thing, that approach doesn't really help.

32
00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:05.580
It's not good due diligence because real due diligence sort

33
00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:09.060
of aligned with international standards is about

34
00:02:09.180 --> 00:02:12.640
understanding risk and acting proportion to that risk.

35
00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:16.820
So when large entities shift compliance burden down to

36
00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:20.350
smaller suppliers just because they can, that's not

37
00:02:20.380 --> 00:02:24.260
responsible action. It creates compliance theater, not really

38
00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:28.260
protection. So that's point one. The second point

39
00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:30.860
that I wanted to raise was around vulnerability.

40
00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:35.200
As we all know, modern slavery is fundamentally about the

41
00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:38.860
abuse of vulnerability. Exploited workers-- Look,

42
00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:42.480
exploiters basically target workers who have no power.

43
00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:46.740
In both our business environments, in both New Zealand and Australia,

44
00:02:47.420 --> 00:02:50.180
there are power imbalances every single day.

45
00:02:50.350 --> 00:02:54.220
A worker's personal circumstances, business practices, lack of

46
00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:57.400
legal protection, all of that matters.

47
00:02:57.430 --> 00:03:01.240
So what we're sort of encouraging businesses to do is flip that mindset.

48
00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:05.540
Use vulnerability as a framework, which then means three things.

49
00:03:06.480 --> 00:03:10.400
One is a pretty obvious one, take responsibility for your

50
00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:13.619
own workers, of course, but also for your indirect workers.

51
00:03:14.420 --> 00:03:17.740
And that's people throughout your supply chain that are at risk.

52
00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:22.020
Second, listen to workers' voices, which is probably

53
00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:25.400
the most valuable data you can find on modern slavery risk.

54
00:03:26.140 --> 00:03:29.980
And work with partners to understand worker views safely

55
00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:33.549
and meaningfully. The third one in that

56
00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:37.500
vulnerability space is, and this one's crucial, is a preventative

57
00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:41.180
mindset. Stop trying to react to problems after they

58
00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:41.580
happen,

59
00:03:42.660 --> 00:03:46.040
but rather set basic standards and address the systemic

60
00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:49.080
factors that create that vulnerability in the first place.

61
00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:53.480
Been doing this now for quite a few years in Australia, and

62
00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:56.480
that seems to work really well.

63
00:03:57.829 --> 00:04:01.670
The last point that I'd like to make is around impact, not

64
00:04:01.700 --> 00:04:05.240
paperwork, which is quite a contentious one sometimes, even

65
00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:06.320
across the Tasman,

66
00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:10.420
but it is probably the most important point as well.

67
00:04:10.460 --> 00:04:14.060
Reporting requirements are increasing. That's fine. That's perfectly fine.

68
00:04:14.160 --> 00:04:17.880
But what our clients tell us is that paper shuffling does not equal

69
00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:18.460
impact.

70
00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:23.100
You can file reports all day and change nothing for vulnerable

71
00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:26.730
workers. What actually works is measuring

72
00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:30.680
effectiveness. Clear metrics that allow businesses

73
00:04:30.720 --> 00:04:31.659
to, A,

74
00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:36.280
identify where their approach isn't working and fix it,

75
00:04:37.380 --> 00:04:41.200
direct resources to what actually matters, and communicate

76
00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:45.260
honestly to stakeholders. And that sort of is a

77
00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:48.860
real demonstration of compliance, not just box ticking, but

78
00:04:49.180 --> 00:04:52.620
actual progress. And so what we're sort of very much in

79
00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:54.110
favor of the bill

80
00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:58.340
sort of promoting and rewarding is it should

81
00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:02.330
incentivize businesses to measure what works, not just

82
00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:05.890
measure how they're reporting. And that's, I think, the

83
00:05:06.080 --> 00:05:09.740
shift we need to see bearing in mind or taking into account the

84
00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:13.250
lessons we've learnt in the UK and in

85
00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:14.080
Australia.

86
00:05:15.020 --> 00:05:17.620
That's the three points that I wanted to make.

87
00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:21.740
So proportionality, vulnerability, and then impact,

88
00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:25.220
not paperwork. Hopefully, that was helpful.

89
00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:28.700
Thank you very much, Nicholas. Can I just ask you, coming to us from somewhere

90
00:05:28.760 --> 00:05:32.580
tropical, you look like you're a different weather or climate to us in New

91
00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:33.040
Zealand.

92
00:05:33.460 --> 00:05:37.360
Look, I'd love to say it's not tropical and beautiful here, but I'm

93
00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:40.220
coming from Currumbin Valley in Queensland.

94
00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:40.920
Ah.

95
00:05:41.760 --> 00:05:42.700
It's very nice.

96
00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:43.800
Right. That explains it

97
00:05:44.870 --> 00:05:44.870
.

98
00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:48.600
Most of the things behind me you see, I planted them with these

99
00:05:48.720 --> 00:05:49.800
hands, basically.

100
00:05:49.870 --> 00:05:49.870
Ah.

101
00:05:49.920 --> 00:05:50.200
So

102
00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:55.040
I feel very special about and very privileged to be in a spot

103
00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:55.640
like this.

104
00:05:56.340 --> 00:05:58.720
Thank you, Nicholas, and helpful to know that you've gone through the Australian

105
00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:01.620
experience, which has added some insight to your

106
00:06:02.720 --> 00:06:05.800
submission. It doesn't appear that we have any questions for you, but can I just

107
00:06:05.840 --> 00:06:06.980
say it's not for a lack of interest.

108
00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:09.100
You've given us a really constructive and insightful

109
00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:12.840
submission in both written and verbally, too.

110
00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:16.000
So thank you for being part of the process. It's very helpful to us.

111
00:06:16.620 --> 00:06:20.520
Appreciate it. You take care and let me know if I can help in any other way.

112
00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:21.820
Thank you so much.

113
00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:23.780
Thanks very much. Bye.

114
00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:24.580
Bye.
